olitical communication. Frédérick Bastien lays out the issues raised by the eroding influence of existing news gatekeepers and the implications of infotainment for politicians, journalists, and citizens, while arguing that infotainment ultimately makes a positive contribution to democratic life by piquing the audience’s interest in public affairs and motivating it to pay more attention to political news in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInfotainment (Television programs). 0aPublic affairs television programs. 0aRadio talk showsxTelevision talk shows. 0aTelevision and politicszQuébec (Province). 0aTelevision and politicszQuébec (Province). 0aTelevision broadcasting of newszQuébec (Province). 0aTelevision programsxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province). 0aTelevision programsxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Media & Internet .2bisacsh1 aRoth, Käthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483684540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774836845423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774836845/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles